  "prompt": "I am having problems with my friend. She is awesome, but she recently got a boyfriend. I just miss the way we once were. She's all over him and her other best friend. What should I do?",
  "response": "It's completely understandable that you're feeling this way. It's tough when a friendship dynamic shifts, especially when a new relationship enters the picture. Here's a breakdown of what you can do:\n\n**1. Acknowledge Your Feelings & Be Honest with Yourself:**\n\n*   **Recognize your emotions:** It's okay to feel jealous, sad, left out, or frustrated. Don't try to suppress these feelings.\n*   **Pinpoint the root:** Are you missing the *quantity* of time you spent together, the *quality* of your conversations, the *shared activities*, or a feeling of being a priority in her life? Understanding what you miss most will help you communicate more effectively.\n*   **Are you jealous of the boyfriend?** Be honest with yourself about whether your feelings are rooted in concern for your friend or a sense of envy about the attention she's giving him.\n\n**2. Consider Her Perspective:**\n\n*   **New relationships are exciting:** It's natural for people to be a bit consumed when they first start dating someone. She's likely excited and wants to share that joy with those closest to her.\n*   **She might not realize how you feel:** She may not be aware of the impact her new relationship is having on your friendship.\n\n**3. Communicate with Her (Tactfully and Openly):**\n\n*   **Choose the right time and place:** Pick a time when you both are relatively relaxed and can have a calm, open conversation. Don't ambush her or bring it up in front of other people.\n*   **Use \"I\" statements:** Focus on your feelings and experiences rather than blaming her. For example:\n    *   Instead of: \"You never spend time with me anymore!\"\n    *   Try: \"I've been feeling a little left out lately, and I miss our one-on-one time.\"\n    *   Instead of: \"You're always with [boyfriend's name]!\"\n    *   Try: \"I understand you're happy, but I sometimes feel like our friendship has changed.\"\n*   **Be specific:** Instead of vague complaints, give specific examples. \"I really missed our weekly coffee dates. Would you be open to still doing those, even if it's just once a month?\"\n*   **Be solution-oriented:** Suggest ways to maintain your friendship while acknowledging her relationship.\n\n**Example Conversation Starter:**\n\n\"Hey [Friend's Name], can we chat for a few minutes? I'm really happy that you've found someone you like, and I can see how happy you are with [Boyfriend's Name]. But I also wanted to be honest and say that I've been missing our time together. I know things change, but I value our friendship a lot, and I was hoping we could find a way to still connect, even with everything else going on.\"\n\n**4. Adjust Your Expectations:**\n\n*   **Things *will* change:** Your friendship will likely not be exactly the same as it was before. Accept that some changes are inevitable.\n*   **Don't expect her to prioritize you over her boyfriend:** It's reasonable to want your friend to still be present in your life, but she also needs to nurture her romantic relationship.\n*   **Be patient:** It may take time for both of you to adjust to the new dynamic.\n\n**5. Focus on Your Own Well-being:**\n\n*   **Invest in other friendships:** Spend time with other friends and build stronger connections with them.\n*   **Pursue your own interests:** Get involved in activities and hobbies that you enjoy. This will help you feel fulfilled and less dependent on your friend for entertainment.\n*   **Remember your value:** Your worth isn't defined by your friend's actions. Remind yourself of your positive qualities and the other meaningful relationships in your life.\n\n**6. Be Open to a Different Kind of Friendship:**\n\n*   **Accept the \"new normal\":** Maybe you see each other less frequently, but when you do, it's still meaningful.\n*   **Friendship can evolve:** Friendships can go through different phases. It doesn't necessarily mean the end of your connection, just a change in its form.\n\n**7. What if She Doesn't Respond Well?**\n\n*   **Give her time:** She might need time to process what you've said.\n*   **Reiterate your feelings (calmly):** If she continues to dismiss your concerns, you can calmly reiterate your feelings one more time.\n*   **Accept the situation (for now):** If she's unwilling to compromise, you may need to accept that your friendship is in a difficult place. Focus on your own well-being and hope that she'll eventually come around.\n*   **Don't become resentful:** Resentment will only damage your own happiness. If you can't move past it, it might be best to create some distance for your own well-being.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **The Other Best Friend:** You mentioned she's also spending time with her other best friend. This could be happening for a number of reasons. Maybe they're both supporting her relationship, or maybe she's simply finding common ground with them on other things. Try not to take this personally.\n*   **Trust:** Trust that your friend values your friendship even if her behavior doesn't always reflect it perfectly.\n\nThis situation is common and, with open communication and understanding, you can hopefully navigate these changes and maintain a meaningful friendship. Good luck!\n",
